0":"1280","Of,,, Portugal":"Portugal","Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain":"Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","Espanha":"Spain","Portugal":"Portugal","Spain":"Spain","Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Espanha":"Toledo, Toledo, Castilla-La Mancha, Spain","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gonçalves","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Fernando, Luis, Domingos, Jorge, Ana, Jaime, Francisco, Alfredo, Armando.  Portuguese Joao, Joaquim, Paulo, Sebastiao, Albano, Catarina, Duarte, Henrique, Marcio, Martinho, Serafim, Terezinha.","Portuguese (<b>Gonçálves</b>): patronymic from the personal name <i>Gonçalo</i> (see   Gonzalo  ). Compare   Gonsalves  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gonzalo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Miguel, Pedro, Albino, Amador, Angelina, Arana, Arnaldo, Blanco, Carlos, Casimiro, Castro, Diego.","Spanish: from the personal name <i>Gonzalo</i>, of Visigothic origin, formed with the element <i>gunth</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Gonsalves","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Fernando, Americo, Joaquin, Jorge, Luis, Miguel, Bernardo, Jose Carlos, Juvenal, Pedro.  Portuguese Joao, Joaquim.","Portuguese: variant of <b>Gonçalves</b> (see   Goncalves  ). This surname is also found in western India, where it was taken by Portuguese colonists."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chancino","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Javier, Salvador, Eduardo, Francisco, Luis, Manuel, Miguel, Pablo, Pedro, Rafael.","Spanish: unexplained. This surname is most common in Mexico and Chile.","Italian (mainly Genoa): probably from a pet form of a medieval personal name documented as <i>Camci</i> and <i>Chanci</i>, of uncertain origin."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ferdinand","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Spanish name, originally <i>Ferdinando</i> (now <i>Hernán</i>), which is of Germanic (Visigothic) origin, derived from <i>farð</i> ‘journey’ (or possibly an altered form of <i>frið</i> ‘peace’) + <i>nand</i> ‘ready, prepared’. This was a traditional name in the royal families of Spain from an early date. It appeared in Britain in the 16th century, having been introduced by Roman Catholic supporters of  Queen Mary I , who married  Philip II  of Spain in  1554 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fernand","meanings":["From a Spanish name, originally <i>Ferdinando</i> (now <i>Hernán</i>), which is of Germanic (Visigothic) origin, derived from <i>farð</i> ‘journey’ (or possibly an altered form of <i>frið</i> ‘peace’) + <i>nand</i> ‘ready, prepared’. This was a traditional name in the royal families of Spain from an early date. It appeared in Britain in the 16th century, having been introduced by Roman Catholic supporters of  Queen Mary I , who married  Philip II  of Spain in  1554 ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ferdinand Gonçalves de Chancino was born in 1235, in Spain, his father, Gonçalo Mendes Chançarel, was 26 and his mother, Marinha Martins Barregão, was 26. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Maior Afonso